AU  - Kipkemboi, J.
TI  - Fingerponds: seasonal integrated aquaculture in East African freshwater wetlands: exploring their potential for wise use strategies.
T2  - Fingerponds: seasonal integrated aquaculture in East African freshwater wetlands: exploring their potential for wise use strategies
M3  - Thesis
AB  - This thesis contains 8 chapters which investigates the potential of integrating aquaculture ponds into smallholder riparian farming systems at the shores of Lake Victoria in Kenya. The introductory chapter provides a background of wetland uses and values, resource trends, integrated farming system concepts, and introduces the study sites and setting of the experimental Fingerpond system in Kenya. Chapters 2 and 3 evaluate the biophysical suitability of Fingerponds in the context of littoral and floodplain wetlands at Lake Victoria. Chapter 4, on the other hand, assesses the aquacultural potential of Fingerponds and the effects of pond management through the addition of manure on water and sediment quality and fish yields. In chapters 5 and 6, the Fingerponds systems are evaluated from a broader farming system perspective, wherein the former assesses the Fingerponds from an agroecosystem perspective using nutrient flows while the latter evaluates the systems in terms of contribution to household food security and livelihoods vis a vis other farming systems. The potential ecological and social implications of introducing Fingerponds into wetlands are addressed in chapter 7. Finally, chapter 8 synthesizes the results of integrated aquaculture in the context of existing farming system and draws conclusions.
