AU  - Yadav, Vinod Kumar
AU  - Qureshi, Neha
TI  - Tilapia-sugarcane integrated farming system for sustainable development of climate-resilient agri-aquaculture.
T2  - Journal of Experimental Zoology, India
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Aquaculture is a significant industry in food production, and its contribution to food and nutrition security is well acknowledged. India's aquaculture production has continued to increase significantly, thus playing a key role in supplying animal protein sources for human consumption. There is a steady increase in Tilapia fish farming in India; however, studies on the efficient use of water and its quality management are scanty. In recent years, farmers in Maharashtra have engaged in aquaculture-crop farming, with those from the Ujjani reservoir area practicing integrated sugarcane farming using tilapia farm discharge water. From this background, the present study assesses the effects of fish farming activities on the aquatic environment by studying tilapia fish farms' water quality in the commanding area of the Ujjani, the second-largest reservoir in Maharashtra. Ten fish farms were selected for the study and two sampling sites were used for each tilapia fish farm; the first sampling point was located upstream of the fish farming facilities, and the second one was downstream from the fish farm discharge point. Collected water samples were analyzed for the measurement of physico-chemical parameters viz. pH, Temperature, Turbidity, Dissolved Oxygen, Chemical Oxygen Demand, Nitrite-N, total ammonia-N, Nitrate-N, Hardness, Alkalinity, Calcium, Sodium and Potassium. Self-paired data of each parameter were analyzed using a student's t-test for paired samples and repeated measure of analysis of variance (ANOVA) was used to detect significant associations (p, 0.05) between these variables and the parameter values in inlet and outlet from the fish farms. The repeated measures of ANOVA were used to analyze the significant differences between water quality across pond number and month at the inlet-outlet. The paired sample t-test result shows that the outlet and inlet water parameters are positively correlated except for temperature and alkalinity, and there is a significant difference between 13 water quality parameters at the inlet and outlet (p<0.05). The repeated measure of ANOVA result revealed that there are significant differences exist between the source and pond number, with nitrite varying in the source and nitrate and ammonia in the source and source-pond number. Hardness, alkalinity, turbidity, and calcium show significant differences in the source and source-month, with calcium varying in source-pond number and source-pond numbermonth. Alkalinity and potassium differ significantly between source and month, while potassium, temperature, PH and DO exhibit significant differences in source and source-pond number. The result shows that the Tilapia fish are enhancing water quality at discharge, and the integrated sugarcane farming with tilapia farm discharge water is playing both an environmentally beneficial role by improving water quality and an economically beneficial role by reducing production costs, increasing productivity, and yielding higher income.
