TI  - The adaptation of small-scale fishery community to coastal resources management and measures on erosion management: a case study in the coastal area of the upper gulf of Thailand.
T2  - Agricultural Innovation for Global Value Chain, Proceedings of 54th Kasetsart University Annual Conference, 2-5 February 2016, Kasetsart University, Thailand. Vol. 1, Plants, Animals, Veterinary Medicine, Fisheries, Agricultural Extension and Home Economics
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - The adaptation of small scale fishery community to coastal management and the factors involved were studied during 2014-2015. Data was collected from 180 fishers and aquaculture farmers by using structural questionnaires. More than two third of samples showed responses and adapted to coastal resources management and measures on coastal erosion in the level of higher than 30%. The average value of adaptation was 40.9% and the quartile deviation was 7.8%. The adaptation involved in opinion on coastal resources management and measures on coastal erosion for 96.3%, living earning behaviors for 23.8%, interdependence to on changes by community participation for 44.4%. The factors which showed the same direction of adaptation were the perception of fishers on coastal resources management and measures on coastal erosion, perception on information and knowledge of coastal resources management and coastal erosion.
