TI  - Special issue on environmental economics in developing countries.
T2  - Journal of Environmental Economics and Management
M3  - Journal issue
AB  - This special issue includes 16 papers focusing on health and economic impacts of environmental issues in developing countries. The topics discussed are: impacts of protected areas and payments for ecosystem services (PES) on forest conservation, poverty reduction, and population change at the locality level in Mexico; effects of formalization of indigenous communities' land rights on deforestation in Brazil; impact of collective incentives in PES in Mexico; minimally invasive temperature sensors to measure the use of fuel-efficient cookstoves as a replacement for three-stone fires in Uganda; association between household electrification and indoor air pollution; adverse health effects of pesticide via drinking water exposure in China; impact of microloans on willingness to pay hygienic latrines in rural Cambodia; effects of an information intervention on household water treatment in Cambodia; demand for information about arsenic testing of drinking water from wells and the household response in India; water scarcity and small-scale social conflict (i.e., riots); economic growth impact of shoreline stabilization policy in Small Island Developing States; relationship of conservation combined with ecotourism to local welfare in Nepal; impacts of fuel conservation policies in the Indian car market; health consequences of exposure to air pollution from coal plants in India; impact of a more stringent wastewater discharge standard imposed on all textile printing and dyeing enterprises on labour demand in China; and, effect of air pollution on labour supply in Peru.
