AU  - Biswarup Saha, Biswarup Saha
AU  - Ram Bahal, Ram Bahal
TI  - Vulnerability and adaptation to different shocks: a livelihood analysis in West Bengal.
T2  - Journal of Interacademicia
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Vulnerability of households to food insecurity, is attributed by different types of shocks such as natural disasters, crop or livestock disease epidemics, price falls of the products, bread winners sudden death in the household and the high incidence and impacts of different illness among the members of the family. The cumulative impacts of these shocks have widespread social and economic effects that threaten the livelihoods of millions of people. This paper depicts the impact of shocks in people's livelihood and to understand how families cope and adapt to different types of shocks. The findings of this study show that labourers and crop farmers and rural artisan are particularly hit hard by any shocks with landless labour class suffered the most. Further, in terms of both exposure to shocks and its impact on the households the Darjeeling district is more vulnerable than Uttar Dinajpur district. The vulnerability index of Darjeeling District is 3.40 while in Uttar Dinajpur District it is 3.29. The region is highly vulnerable to natural disaster, market fluctuation and moderately vulnerable to illness, pest and diseases of crops and bread winner's death. The household under different livelihood groups adopted different ex-ante accumulation strategies to fight against different unforeseen shocks of the future. Most common accumulation strategies was income diversification (45.83%) followed by asset building (31.25%). Vulnerable households in this region heavily depended on borrowings as ex-post strategies, particularly from relatives, landlords, moneylenders, and other informal sources and that too at a higher rate of interests. Besides, consumption diversification, eroding of assets and migration are the other ex-post coping strategies adopted by different households. Households with better education, owning productive assets like land or cattle, having non-farm employment opportunities, income diversification and access to resources, higher social participation and markets are less vulnerable. All these have a large contribution in household income. Therefore, improving the ability of the poor to cope with vulnerability is the best way to reduce the impact of different shocks.
