AU  - Salza, Alberto
TI  - Drought and floods at Lake Turkana: an anomaly for pastoralists?
T2  - Nomadic Peoples
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This article discusses how drought and floods, which are often attributed to climate change, leave an impact on the livelihoods of pastoralists around Lake Turkana in Kenya. The floods occurring around Lake Turkana are of two types: (a) rising lake waters submerging lowlands near the coast; and (b) flash floods out of dry river beds(lugga). In the second case, pastoralists acknowledge a delay effect: rainwater collects underground and fills their hand-dug wells months after the rains, sometimes with unexpected intensity. Pastoralists are aware of the risk, and seldom make camp inside alugga. It also points out the effect of drought on the quality of baddan trees(Balanites aegyptiaca)which the camels feed on. Furthermore, the paper describes the behaviour and adaptation of pastoralists towards climate change.
