TI  - Plant biotechnology and agricultural production: the experience of Mozambique.
T2  - Aspects of Applied Biology
M3  - Journal article
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Mozambique is a country located in sub-Saharan Africa, where rainfall is erratic and minimal for the demands of the crops, but still rich in natural resources. Small scale farmers, who represent the majority of the whole agricultural sector, are almost totally dependent on the rainfall and on the exploitation of the resources at their location for different purposes. Under these conditions, the agricultural production is low, perpetuating poverty and other developing countries-related problems. Additionally, some plant species are endangered contributing to the reduction of the genetic diversity. Therefore, Plant Biotechnology has the potential for improving the agricultural production and natural resources conservation. This paper describes the present agricultural production of the country and points out ways of overcoming the situation through the use of Plant Biotechnology as a tool for development.
