TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ncube, B.
TI  - Insights into indigenous knowledge strategies for coping and adapting to drought in agriculture: a Karoo scenario, South Africa.
T2  - Indilinga. African Journal of Indigenous Knowledge Systems
M3  - Journal article
AB  - South Africa experienced one of the worst droughts in history during the 2014-2017 period with 2015 recording the lowest rainfall since 1904. Response to drought is usually focused on scientific solutions, ignoring local approaches. The article presents results of a three-year interaction with farmers in the semi-arid Karoo region of South Africa. The research aimed to document coping and adaptation strategies adopted by farmers during drought. Data were collected using semi-structured interviews, focus group discussions, and observations every three to four months, for periods of up to two weeks at a time. Validation workshops and information sessions were also held where additional information was collected. In total 101 farmers were interviewed during farm visits, an additional 84 were consulted during information sessions, and 14 extension officers were consulted. A wideranging list of indigenous drought indicators was compiled, including the appearance of certain species and prevailing wind direction. Vegetable farmers had devised simple methods of conserving moisture and improving soil fertility. Farmers in mixed croplivestock systems manipulated irrigation cycles and switched to drought-resistant livestock. Livestock farmers moved animals to wetter areas; some used stored lucerne (Medicago sativa) to feed livestock, while others practised effective grazing management. Generational indigenous knowledge had been preserved in old farms. Recommendations from the research include training extension officers in indigenous knowledge, improving early warning systems, and setting up programs to implement some of the identified strategies with newly resettled farmers.
