AU  - Adoga, P. A.
AU  - Idris, H. A.
TI  - Climate variability and agricultural resilience in Makurdi, Lafia, Ibi, Jos, and Lokoja of the north central region of Nigeria.
T2  - Journal of Applied Sciences and Environmental Management
M3  - Journal article
AB  - Climate variability, especially rainfall trends, significantly affect agricultural resilience in North Central Nigeria. Hence, the objective of this paper is to evaluate the Climate Variability and Agricultural Resilience in Makurdi, Lafia, Ibi, Jos, and Lokoja of the Middle Belt Region of Nigeria using a mixed-methods approach that combines surveys with rainfall data for a period of 40-60 years. The data for Rainfall Trend show that Ibi recorded the highest peaks of the five states with an annual rainfall of 2532 mm in 2019, Lafia showed a 4 years consecutive high annual rainfall of 1916.5 mm in 2017, 2515.6 mm in 2018, 2240.8 mm in 2019 and 2029.7 mm in 2020. Ibi has the lowest annual rainfall of 719 mm in 2013, followed by Makurdi with 770.7 mm in 2004. The results show an increasing trend in rainfall for three towns: Ibi, Lafia and Lokoja, stable trend for Makurdi and declining trends for Jos. This variability has also impacted crop yields and livestock productivity, and led to the adoption of diverse coping strategies by farmers and herders. The findings of this study have implications for enhancing agricultural resilience and promoting sustainable livelihoods in the region and recommended the provision of timely and accessible weather forecasts and early warning systems tailored to local farmers and herders, investing in Climate-Smart Agriculture (CSA) techniques such as the development and use of drought-resistant seeds, conservation agriculture, and integrated crop-livestock systems to build resilience against climate shocks, enhance water management infrastructure, support local adaptation initiatives as well as promote farmer-herder dialogue and conflict resolution.
