AU  - Lahiri-Dutt, K.
TI  - Experiencing and coping with change: women-headed farming households in the Eastern Gangetic Plains.
T2  - ACIAR Technical Reports Series
M3  - Bulletin
AB  - This technical report is the outcome of a field survey undertaken in 2012 of women heads of households from selected districts in Bihar and West Bengal (India) and in the Eastern Terai region of Nepal. The main objective of the research was to provide a set of recommendations, based on the data generated from the survey, to integrate gender into a larger Australian Centre for International Agricultural Research (ACIAR) project on climate-resilient agriculture in the Eastern Gangetic Plains (EGP). The survey explored: the characteristics of the women heads and their households; women's multiple roles; women's access to and control over assets and resources; perceptions of changes in farming practices; general problems, shocks, worries and needs; and the general attitudes to empowerment and wellbeing, and climate change. Recommendations for developing projects targeted at women heads of households in the EGP include: incorporating 'gender mainstreaming' into the design of projects; investigating solutions to labour shortages; recognizing diversity between local contexts and individual circumstances; helping to form community support for women heads of households, to assist them to secure both financial and technical support; involving men in gender-equity processes; building capacity of women heads of households; and improving women's access to information, markets and transport.
