AU  - Mehar, Mamta
AU  - Prasad, Narayan
TI  - Climate change, adaptation and gender: policy, practice and methodological underpinnings.
T2  - Climate change, adaptation and gender: policy, practice and methodological underpinnings
M3  - Book
AB  - This book offers a wide, in-depth study of the gender-climate change-agriculture nexus. The prime objectives of the book are to uniquely explore every dimension of climate change (i.e. people's beliefs or perceptions, knowledge, experience, coping, adaptation and mitigation strategies) and link it with gender, including new theoretical and methodological approaches that go beyond the household as the unit of analysis and include approaches that include intersectional analysis. Each of the chapters draws on theory and concepts related to agricultural, rural or sustainable development. Several of the chapters also engage with new ways of analysing gender and climate change in an interdisciplinary way. The book includes procedural details of social research together with lessons learned and recommendations from the people involved in the study. The literature review brings critical arguments for gender inclusion, comparisons and commonalities across studies with respect to adoption of climate-resilient practices, especially by smallholder farmers. Lastly, it provides methodological prescriptions for ongoing and future research. The book has 13 chapters, a glossary, a list of reference guides and web sites, and a subject index.
