TI  - Impacts of flash flood on agricultural livelihoods in upland areas: a case study of rice production in Nathen Village, Kasi District, Vientiane Province, Lao PDR.
T2  - Proceedings, International Conference on Interdisciplinary Research and Development (ICIRD), 29-31 October 2015, Maejo University, Chiang Mai, Thailand
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - The objectives of this quantitative and qualitative study were to: (1) explore impacts of flash flood on the farmers' livelihoods, particularly on rice production and (2) identify coping strategies of the farmers against the flash flood in relation to gender role; Kasi district is located in the north of Vientiane province, Lao PDR and it was selected as a case study. A set of structured interview schedules was used for data collection administered with 40 flood affected households. Besides, in-depth interview was conducted with15 households and some informants of government agencies, village heads, and non-government organizations (NGOs). Findings showed that many households had experienced several heavy flash floods caused by overflow of the Likriverdue to unusual heavy rain and storm. The flash flood affected their agricultural production areas, livestocks, household assets, health care, and other facilities. When faced with flash flood, the community employed strategies i.e. risk reduction, risk mitigation, and risk coping. Local communities were given the power to decide and select an appropriate flash flood risk management strategy such as distribution of in-kind support.
