AU  - Olowa, O. W.
TI  - The effect of livestock pilferage on household poverty in developing countries: theoretical evidence from Nigeria.
T2  - Bangladesh e-Journal of Sociology
M3  - Journal article
AB  - While livestock pilferages in Nigeria primarily caused by increased poverty among unemployed workers and drought stricken crop farmers, its effect on stock farmers can be devastating. It reduces the affected households' own consumption of both the "returns" on their wealth, e.g. milk and wool, and of wealth itself, e.g. meat and hides. In addition, it restricts their ability to sell their returns and wealth in the market place and use the proceeds to acquire other food and non-food products. Some policy implications are also highlighted.
