AU  - Manipadma Jena, Manipadma Jena
TI  - Food insecurity among tribal communities of Orissa.
T2  - Economic and Political Weekly
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This report examines food insecurity in the district of Rayagada, Orissa in India, and the existence of communities' voices that may be seeking to ensure accountability in service delivery of the many different schemes being executed to ensure food security. The gram panchayat and in particular the gram sabha, is meant and best equipped to act as the voice of the tribal people. But in reality, the social, nutritional and economic development programmes are decided by the central and state governments. While the one-third reservation of panchayat seats for women has contributed little to truly empower the tribal women of Rayagada, they are getting relatively more empowered as catalysts of change. This undercurrent of change has completely transformed the status of the tribal community of Badahansa. While lack of community involvement in the functioning of the anganwadi centre (AWC) is to be seen in most communities, not so in Badahansa, where women not only actively monitor the general functioning of their AWC, but also contribute food to the centre. It is seen that when women earn better, the household spends more on food and health needs. Food assistance is most essential to mitigate disaster-induced food shortages, either of small groups or an entire village and women's collectives are increasingly gearing up to provide this emergency food security. Community grain banks are the older forms of community preparedness and long-term empowerment to tackle food insecurity in Rayagada since the 1980's. But the grain banks are again breaking down due to widespread default of grain loans. Due to increasing population, shrinking cultivable land and deforestation due to industrialization, shifting cultivation intensified with fallow cycles reduced to two-three years in many areas leaving most slopes completely degraded. The absence of ownership is also a disincentive for the tribal farmer to invest in resuscitating the land. The net result is that the primary source of food becomes that much more insecure.
