TI  - Climate change and sex-specific labor intensity: an empirical analysis in Africa.
T2  - Global Food Security
M3  - Journal article
AB  - This paper examines how women and men adapt their participation intensity in agricultural employment in response to extreme weather events, using a novel dataset from 31 African labor-force and other household surveys. The dataset is matched with gridcell monthly time series bioclimatic variables. Results suggest heat waves reduce the hours worked in agriculture by 40%. Similarly, drought shocks reduce the number of hours worked in agriculture by 14%. Women farmers experience 40% lesser reduction compared to their male counterparts.
