AU  - Mesfin, W.
TI  - Crop mix and resource use pattern under risk: the case of smallholder farmers in eastern highlands of Ethiopia.
T2  - International Journal of Agriculture and Crop Sciences (IJACS)
M3  - Journal article
AB  - The study analyzed the major sources of risk, coping mechanisms and crop mix and resource use pattern of smallholder farmers under risk based on data generated from 175 households in eastern Ethiopia. Descriptive statistics and risk programming model were used for data analysis. The study identified drought, pests and diseases, poor market bargaining power, lack of disease resistant varieties, soil fertility decline and high input prices as the prominent sources of risks in the study area. In order to safeguard themselves against these risks, farmers employ different forms of crop diversification. The risk programming model result signifies that farmers in the study areas are risk averse and they are much oriented towards risk-minimization. Based on the results of the study, it was suggested that the extension system in the country should include risk-minimization as a strategy instead of sticking only on profit maximization goal. Investment on soil conservation, irrigation projects and development and dissemination of disease and drought resistant varieties for the farmers are important to deal with the prominent risks. Proper application of fertilizer or shift to substitutes will reduce its risk effect. In addition, there is need for mutual efforts by the government, research and extension agencies in order to make new technologies available and policies that would help farmers operate within the developed risk efficient farm plans.
