AU  - Twyman, J.
AU  - Muriel, J.
AU  - Clavijo, M.
TI  - Report of a Gender Survey in Cauca, Colombia.
T2  - Reporte Encuesta de Genero Cauca, Colombia
M3  - Miscellaneous
AB  - The present document is the preliminary result of the intra-household survey that was conducted among 198 households from the Climate Adaptable Sustainable Territory (TeSAC) of the CCAFS programme in Popayan, department of Cauca, Colombia, between October and November 2014. The questionnaire was composed of 15 modules and was addressed to men and women decision makers in households. Questions included were related topics on agricultural activities, land and asset ownership, decision making, climate information, risk perceptions, and household members' roles. From the total number of households, responses were obtained from 160 men and 168 women. This report presents the descriptive statistics, at the household level and at the individual level. Descriptive statistics at the individual level show differences as well as similarities between the responses of men and women. In general, there are differences in knowledge about sustainable climate-friendly practices (CSA), women tend to have less knowledge about climate change than men, and there is a clear gap in access to different sources of agricultural information. However, it is the women who are more likely to adopt CSA practices and use climate information to plan their agricultural and domestic activities. A high percentage of respondents, both women and men, reported having noticed changes in climate, mainly associated with increases in temperature. The main concerns about future climate change for both men and women are related to droughts and heat. But despite these concerns, few responded by taking action to protect themselves, their families or the community.
