TI  - Impact of climate change on livelihood assets in farming community: a case study in selected townships in Central Dry Zone of Myanmar.
T2  - Proceedings of the Tenth Agricultural Research Conference, Yezin Agricultural University, Nay Pyi Raw, Myanmar, 11-12 January 2017
M3  - Conference paper
AB  - Rural populations are undergoing rapid changes in both their livelihoods and land uses, with associated impacts on ecosystems, global biogeochemistry, and climate change. This study was conducted at Tatkon, Nyaung U and Meiktila Townships in October 2015, April 2016 and November 2016. The objectives of this study were to identify the livelihoods of the farmers, and to assess the impact of climate change on livelihood assets in farming community in selected townships. Quantitative and qualitative data were collected by using structured interview schedule questionnaire and in-depth interviewing method. The income sources of household were agriculture in Tatkon, agriculture and services in Nyaung U and remittance from migration in Meiktila Township. Respondents raised cattle, pig, chicken, goat and sheep for their farming, extra income and home consumption in all selected townships. Significant changes of at household and community levels affected by adverse weather conditions during study period were found in selected townships. Changes on environmental factor effect on access of extension services and advice (social capital), migration pattern and income situations (financial capital) of respondents at household level and social activities at community level (social and physical capitals). The respondents from selected township noticed environmental changes during study period. Offering extension advice to farmers in 2016 was decreased in all selected townships compare with 2015 summer. The farmers in the selected areas faced the drought, flood and windy in 2015, however, the shock was minor. Although same shocks were found in 2016 summer and monsoon seasons, the impact was more serious and effect on their livelihood assets especially social and financial capitals leading to positive impact on in social and physical capitals in study areas. The farmers responded to these changes by re-cultivating next crops, selling valuables things, pawning valuables things and pumping underground water.
